"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819314?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲热浪期间，罗马的餐馆设置了喷雾风扇。预计到本周中旬欧洲的高温将会加剧。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Gaia Squarci/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819318?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">雅典卫城是雅典的主要旅游景点，即使在上周的热浪期间，雅典卫城也挤满了游客。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Angelos Tzortzinis/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p></p>撒丁岛桑卢里市长阿尔贝托·乌尔皮 (Alberto Urpi) 表示，当局已对该地区发布天气红色警报，建议人们从上午晚些时候到下午 6 点呆在室内。<p></p><p> “我们准备好了，”乌尔皮说。 “我们已经习惯了这些热浪，并且有时间组织我们的应对措施。”</p><p>由于天气炎热，当局在周五和周六的大部分时间里关闭了雅典卫城。预计希腊首都本周气温将保持在 97 度以上，周日最高温度接近 110 度。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0AD43FBB-1726-4D5C-9BCE-DF4AF94D3260&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fextreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">随着酷热席卷南欧，野火摧毁了雅典郊外的建筑物并烧毁了大片土地。非洲大陆的其他地区以及中国和美国都遭受了创纪录的气温打击。照片：Petros Giannakouris/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>亚洲</h3><p>另一场热浪同时席卷亚洲部分地区。据官方媒体报道，中国新疆西北部地区的一个村庄创下了 126 度的历史最高气温。</p><p>热浪期间，美国气候特使约翰·克里会见了包括北京最高外交政策特使王毅和国务院总理李强在内的中国官员，讨论如何加速脱碳和其他气候变化目标。中国和美国是世界上最大的温室气体排放国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819325?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国气候特使约翰·克里正在北京恢复有关减少温室气体排放的双边合作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：弗洛伦斯·洛-普尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819328?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">上周，南京市民在防空洞避暑。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/NurPhoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>世界气象组织的席尔瓦表示，目前该地区有高压系统滞留热空气。这些系统将在接下来的几天内保持不变。</p><p> “It&#39;s moving very slowly, but we will not have this situation forever,” Silva said.</p><p> Write to Alyssa Lukpat at <a href="mailto:alyssa.lukpat@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alyssa.lukpat@wsj.com</a> , Joseph De Avila at <a href="mailto:joseph.deavila@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joseph.deavila@wsj.com</a> , Eric Niiler at <a href="mailto:eric.niiler@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.niiler@wsj.com</a> , Eric Sylvers at <a href="mailto:eric.sylvers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.sylvers@wsj.com</a> and Margherita Stancati at <a href="mailto:margherita.stancati@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">margherita.stancati@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 20:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d <author><![CDATA[Alyssa LukpatJoseph De AvilaEric NiilerEric SylversMargherita Stancati]]></author><category> WSJSpeeddesk</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>global</category><category>世界问题</category><category>weather </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Lots of Tap Water Contains ‘Forever Chemicals.’ These Steps Reduce Your Risk.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>您无法完全避免有毒的 PFAS 化学物质，但您可以减少在家中的接触<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818375/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>图片由《华尔街日报》提供，ISTOCK<span>图片由《华尔街日报》提供，ISTOCK</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060204"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060204"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sumathi-reddy"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-733259/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sumathi-reddy" itemprop="url" rel="author">苏马蒂·雷迪</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 18 日下午 3:30（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pfas-forever-chemicals-how-to-reduce-654cd05b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>有毒的“ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-are-forever-chemicals-and-are-they-hazardous-to-your-health-11671563642?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">永久化学物质</a>”遍布你的家。但过滤水可以减少您的接触。</p><p>这些合成化学品也称为 PFAS， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-forever-chemicals-are-all-around-us-from-winter-coats-to-fast-food-wrappers-5a250b05?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">长期以来一直用于消费品中</a>，出现在从化妆品、牙线到地毯、雨衣和不粘锅的各种物品中。它们与包括癌症在内的许多健康问题有关。 PFAS 被称为“永远的化学物质”，因为它们需要很长时间才能分解，它分布广泛，但很难判断特定产品是否含有它们。</p><p>这些化学物质损害您健康的主要方式是您吃、喝或吸入它们。您的饮用水可能是家中最大的风险：根据美国地质调查局最近的一项研究， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nearly-half-of-u-s-tap-water-contains-forever-chemicals-study-says-985f6467?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">近一半的美国自来水</a>受到 PFAS 污染。</p><p>此外，地毯和室内装潢中的 PFAS 化学物质可能会脱落并被吸入。科罗拉多公共卫生学院安舒茨医学院公共卫生实践副院长 Ned Calonge 表示，有一些有限的证据表明，你可以通过穿衣服或接触含有 PFAS 的东西来吸收这些化学物质。</p><p> “你确实无法避免所有接触，但你可以尝试避免一些常见的来源，”华盛顿特区非营利组织环境工作组的高级科学家塔莎·斯托伊伯说。</p><p>以下是有关您家中永久化学物质的信息以及如何降低风险。</p><h3>为什么这些化学物质有害？</h3><p> PFAS 是全氟烷基物质和多氟烷基物质的简写，是包含非常强的碳氟键的化学物质。这些化学物质具有特殊的性质，使其成为防水、防污渍和防油脂产品中受欢迎的成分。但这种结合也使得 PFAS 难以在环境和我们的体内分解，它们可以在其中保留多年。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818480?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：《华尔街日报》、ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据美国疾病控制与预防中心的数据，几乎每个人 <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2072821/" target="_blank" class="icon none">的血液中都含有一定水平的 PFAS</a> 。您可以询问您的医生关于测试您血液中 PFAS 水平的事宜。</p><p>杰基·古德里奇说，这些化学物质与多种健康问题有关，包括高胆固醇、某些类型的癌症和免疫反应下降。</p>密歇根大学环境健康科学研究副教授。<p></p><p>许多公司在 2000 年代初期停止使用其中两种最常见的化学品，即 PFOA 和 PFOS。其他人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/3m-to-stop-making-discontinue-use-of-forever-chemicals-11671541938?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正在逐步淘汰它们</a>。但科学家表示，一些公司正在使用可能具有类似有害特性的替代品。</p><h3>如何减少自来水中的 PFAS</h3><p>科学家表示，饮用水是 PFAS 暴露最普遍、最有害的来源之一。另一方面，疾病预防控制中心表示，在含有 PFAS 的水中淋浴或洗碗<a href="https://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/pfas/health-effects/PFAS-exposure-and-your-body.html" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">不被认为是一种风险</a>。</p><p>今年早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/epa-proposes-regulations-for-forever-chemicals-in-drinking-water-b6963dfd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，美国环保署提议对公共饮用水中的某些 PFAS 化合物进行联邦限制</a>，该计划可能会在年底前最终确定。与此同时，专家表示您可以采取一些措施。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818447?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：《华尔街日报》、ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>联系当地的自来水公司，看看他们是否正在测量 PFAS 以及含量是多少，说</p>Aleksandra Szczuka，密歇根大学土木与环境工程助理教授。<p></p><p>使用常用的过滤器来过滤自来水。 <a href="https://www.ewg.org/research/getting-forever-chemicals-out-drinking-water-ewgs-guide-pfas-water-filters" target="_blank" class="icon none">EWG 最近的一项研究</a>评估了 10 种不同的过滤器，发现其中四种可以将水中的 PFAS 减少 100% 或接近 100%。其中包括 Clearly Filtered、Epic Water Filter、ZeroWater 和 Travel Berkey。</p><p>流行品牌 Brita 的六杯水罐可减少水中 66% 的 PFAS，而 PUR 的七杯水罐可减少 79% 的 PFAS。</p><p> Stoiber 说，从饮用水中去除 PFAS 的最有效方法是在家中安装反渗透系统。它们需要安装在水槽下方，您可以从 Home Depot 等商店购买。</p><p>她说，如果您从私人水井取水，您可能需要对其进行 PFAS 和其他污染物检测。您当地的水务部门可能会测试样品，或者您也可以找到一个独立的实验室。</p><h3>地毯和室内装潢怎么样？</h3><p>很难确定您的地毯或沙发是否含有 PFAS。一个可能的指标是产品何时以防污或防污的名义销售。您也可以致电或发送电子邮件给制造商询问。</p><p>包括<a href="https://corporate.homedepot.com/news/sustainability/phasing-out-products-containing-pfas#.XYD8x-3waIo.twitter" target="_blank" class="icon none">家得宝 (Home Depot)</a> 、 <a href="https://corporate.lowes.com/our-responsibilities/corporate-responsibility-reports-policies/lowes-safer-chemicals-policy" target="_blank" class="icon none">劳氏 (Lowe&#39;s</a> ) 和<a href="https://about.ikea.com/en/about-us/our-view-on/chemicals" target="_blank" class="icon none">宜家 (IKEA)</a>在内的一些公司已宣布将逐步淘汰地毯中的 PFAS。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818445?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：《华尔街日报》、ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>警惕声称产品不含某种特定 PFAS 化学物质（例如 PFOA）的营销。 “这意味着他们可能有不同的东西，”古德里奇说。</p><p>东北大学社会科学环境健康研究所所长 Phil Brown 表示，含有 PFAS 的地毯可能会不断脱落化学物质。科学家表示，目前尚不清楚这种脱落是否会随着时间的推移而减少或增加，或者在清洗或蒸汽清洁时会减少。</p><p>当然，您可以尝试将所有地毯更换为您确定不含 PFAS 的地毯。除此之外，你可以通过经常吸尘、拖地和除尘来减少家庭灰尘，位于加利福尼亚州伯克利的非营利组织绿色科学政策研究所表示。</p><p>尝试使用带有 HEPA 过滤器和机械动力头的真空吸尘器。您还可以在地毯上放置未经 PFAS 处理的游戏垫或地毯。</p><h3>其他需要检查的家居用品</h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818446?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：《华尔街日报》、ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>卡隆赫说，从受 PFAS 污染的水中捕获的鱼、用 PFAS 制成的牙线以及用含有 PFAS 的材料包装的食品都存在潜在风险。PFAS 因其耐油脂特性而常用于快餐容器。</p><p>很难知道产品是否含有 PFAS——许多产品都没有列出它们所含有的化学物质。 <a href="https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.estlett.1c00240" target="_blank" class="icon none">2021 年一项针对化妆品的研究</a>发现，即使在列出成分的产品中，即使未列出，也可能存在 PFAS。</p><p>许多不粘锅都是用 PFAS 制成的。卡隆赫说，如果表面仍然完好无损，化学物质就不会渗入你的食物中，但如果表面被划伤，你应该把它扔掉。环境工作组表示，即使不粘锅声称不含 PFAS，但用铸铁、玻璃、不锈钢或碳钢制成的锅具烹饪仍然更安全。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您是否正在采取任何措施来预防和尽量减少家中的有害化学物质？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>写信给Sumathi Reddy： <a href="mailto:Sumathi.Reddy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Sumathi.Reddy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 19:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pfas-forever-chemicals-how-to-reduce-654cd05b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pfas-forever-chemicals-how-to-reduce-654cd05b<author><![CDATA[Sumathi Reddy]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>化学品</category><category>基本材料/资源</category><category>产品/消费者安全</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>环境健康</category><category>癌症</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>自然资源稀缺</category><category>塑料污染</category><category>环境污染</category><category>水污染</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>产品</category><category>消费者安全</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>服务</category><category>环境健康</category><category>癌症</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>自然资源稀缺</category><category>塑料污染</category><category>环境污染</category><category>水污染</category><category>化学品</category><category>基础材料</category><category>资源</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Europe Tries to Bridge Its Migration Divide]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Migration pact with Tunisia is EU&#39;s latest step to resolve toxic fights over migration within bloc <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818690/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="The Tunisian coast guard tries to stop migrants off the coast off Sfax, Tunisia, earlier this year." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The Tunisian coast guard tries to stop migrants off the coast off Sfax, Tunisia, earlier this year. JIHED ABIDELLAOUI/REUTERS <span>JIHED ABIDELLAOUI/REUTERS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060991"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060991"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Laurence Norman</a></span> in Berlin and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/margherita-stancati" itemprop="url" rel="author">Margherita Stancati</a></span> in Rome</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 18, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-tries-to-bridge-its-migration-divide-c8b1707c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Europe is trying again to resolve its most divisive issue: migration.</p><p> After years of bad blood and legal fights, the European Union is edging toward a tough new set of migration and asylum policies, including steps to ease turning people away.</p><p> The EU on Sunday secured the first piece of its plan by signing an agreement with Tunisia that promises economic aid and other cooperation in return for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tunisian-president-targets-sub-saharan-african-migrants-mob-violence-follows-7a51495a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Tunisian efforts</a> to crack down on boat crossings and to take back Tunisians illegally entering the bloc.</p><p> Migration into Europe and across the Americas has risen sharply since the end of the Covid-19 pandemic, prompting <strong>&nbsp;</strong> renewed efforts to tighten restrictions on inflows. The Biden administration recently unveiled <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-new-immigration-system-works-after-title-42-ends-2fba7498?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">new limits on asylum seekers</a> by declaring that migrants who transited through another country on their way to the US without seeking asylum there would now be ineligible to stay in the US</p><p> Europe&#39;s new approach has been spearheaded by Italian Prime Minister Giorgia Meloni, whose <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-shipwreck-shakes-italys-anti-immigration-government-b35a6d81?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">antimigration stance</a> helped her sweep to victory in parliamentary elections last year.</p><p> Questions remain about whether the EU&#39;s plans will significantly dent the number of people seeking to cross illegally into Europe—and whether the proposals will be fully enacted. Migration groups argue that the EU should reopen safe and legal pathways to the bloc, after a tragedy in June when hundreds of asylum seekers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/greece-migrant-ship-reveals-perilous-route-to-europe-260dd49b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are presumed to have died</a> off the Greek coast after the overcrowded fishing vessel transporting them sank. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818707?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Migrants at the immigrant reception facility on the Sicilian island of Lampedusa last month.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: vincenzo livieri/EPA/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818692?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> This image taken from a rescue helicopter shows migrants aboard a fishing vessel shortly before the boat sank off the coast of Greece last month, leaving hundreds presumed dead.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: HELLENIC COASTGUARD/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The plans still face opposition from Poland and Hungary, which previously sued the European Commission, the EU&#39;s executive body, over an earlier migration proposal. The new plans will also need backing from the European Parliament, which has traditionally opposed efforts to restrict asylum seekers&#39; rights.</p><p> Since <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/migrant-crisis-divides-europe-1441314666?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the 2015 migration crisis</a> , when over one million asylum seekers, mainly Syrians, fled across the Mediterranean Sea into the bloc, migration has sparked toxic arguments among the 27 EU members. The fights have at times paralyzed decision-making on other policies.</p><p> After sealing a deal with Turkey in 2016 that essentially paid Ankara to keep Syrians from entering the bloc, EU member states have repeatedly failed to agree on a comprehensive system to control illegal immigration while complying with international obligations to give shelter to refugees who need protection. For the past few years, they hadn&#39;t even bothered trying.</p><p> The volatile politics of migration has shown no signs of abating. Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte&#39;s government recently fell over the issue. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/immigration-backlashes-spread-around-the-world-142124bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Antimigration parties are faring well</a> in opinion polls in several EU countries, including Austria, the Netherlands and Spain, and are well-placed to add seats in next year&#39;s European Parliament elections.</p><p> EU diplomats nonetheless last month managed to piece together an overwhelming majority agreement on a new approach to the issue, which managed to blend Meloni&#39;s antimigration focus with longstanding demands from some west European capitals for shared EU responsibility for asylum seekers.</p><p> The proposal would allow countries to prescreen refugees and process people deemed unlikely to gain entrance through a swift evaluation. It would also give each member state more authority over where a failed asylum seeker could be returned to.</p><p> In exchange <strong>,</strong> the EU would seek to relocate at least 30,000 migrants across the bloc annually. <strong>&nbsp;</strong> If a country refused to take in asylum seekers, they could instead make a <strong>&nbsp;</strong> 20,000-euro payment, equivalent to roughly $22,500, for each person they don&#39;t accept.</p><p> While the migration deal was being cobbled together, the EU announced that European Commission President Ursula von der Leyen would travel with Meloni and Rutte to Tunisia for talks on a migration pact. The trio returned to seal last weekend&#39;s deal. In June, <strong>&nbsp;</strong> von der Leyen proposed creating a fund of more than $15 billion to finance external partnerships like the Tunisia deal. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="486" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818702?width=700&amp;height=486" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> From left, Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte, European Commission President Ursula von der Leyen, Tunisian President Kais Saied and Italian Prime Minister Giorgia Meloni on Sunday after the deal was struck with Tunisia.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tunisian Presidency/APA Images/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> At the center of the EU negotiations has been Meloni, whose right-wing government made tackling migration a top foreign-policy priority. <strong>&nbsp;</strong> Previous antimigrant champions have tended to pick fights with Brussels. She has generally worked with the EU to achieve her goals.</p><p> More than 76,000 migrants have arrived by sea to Italy so far this year, equivalent to roughly 77% of registered Mediterranean Sea arrivals to Europe, according to United Nations data.</p><p> The number of arrivals to Europe&#39;s southern shores is nearly twice as high as it was during the first half of last year—and is the highest level since the migration crisis years of 2015.</p><p> A big reason for the increased flow of sea arrivals is Tunisia&#39;s political and economic turmoil. Kais Saied, the country&#39;s authoritarian president, has spearheaded a campaign against sub-Saharan African migrants in Tunisia that has contributed to the instability.</p><p> On Monday, Amnesty International criticized the EU&#39;s deal with Tunisia, saying it signaled “EU acceptance of increasingly repressive behavior” by Saied and the Tunisian government. “This makes the European Union complicit in the suffering that will inevitably result,” Amnesty said.</p><p> Meloni is showing no sign of regrets. On Sunday, she hailed the Tunisia agreement as a “model” for building new relationships between European and North African countries. In recent weeks, she has been trying to bring Poland and Hungary, two countries with similar right-wing, nationalist political brands, on board.</p><p> Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orban and Polish Prime Minister Mateusz Morawiecki, who have long opposed any mandatory mechanism to share asylum seekers across the continent, came to a Brussels summit last month determined to denounce the deal and the way it was reached—without their backing.</p><p> Morawiecki said on his way to the summit that loose migration policies had led to blood being spilled in Europe&#39;s streets. The two men refused to back down over hours of talks that ran late into the night and blocked the summit statement on migration.</p><p> A few days later, Meloni headed to Warsaw for talks with Morawiecki. “There is no division between us on this because we have the same, key objective, which isn&#39;t to discuss how to handle illegal migration in Europe, but how to stop it,” she said at a joint press conference with Morawiecki. “We will continue working together to find solutions that are effective for everyone.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="835" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818730?width=1260&amp;height=835" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Migrants whose boats were intercepted by Tunisian authorities are seen in Sfax, Tunisia.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Hasan Mrad/IMAGESLIVE/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Laurence Norman at <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a> and Margherita Stancati at <a href="mailto:margherita.stancati@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">margherita.stancati@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-tries-to-bridge-its-migration-divide-c8b1707c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-tries-to-bridge-its-migration-divide-c8b1707c<author><![CDATA[Laurence NormanMargherita Stancati]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Despite Ukraine War, U.K. Set to Shrink Its Army]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>新军事战略的重点是装备更好的部队和更多的弹药<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062646"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818395?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰陆军新兵与英国皇家海军陆战队成员一起参加训练课程。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亨利·尼科尔斯/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062646"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/max-colchester" itemprop="url" rel="author">马克斯·科尔切斯特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 18 日上午 8:03 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/despite-ukraine-war-u-k-set-to-shrink-its-army-422e1424"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伦敦——随着俄罗斯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的侵略</a>迫使欧洲最大的军费开支国和乌克兰的一个重要盟友重新审视其战略，英国将精简军队，并寻求建立一支装备更精良的部队，并表示可以更快地动员起来。</p><p>英国国防部周二公布的新战略计划旨在回应对英国军队的批评，分析人士称，在俄罗斯和乌克兰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在欧洲打陆战</a>之际，英国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europes-defense-dilemma-to-buy-or-not-to-buy-american-1576c2f4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">军队缺乏有效的装备和弹药</a>。</p><p>自冷战结束以来，英国军队已从主要驻扎欧洲的常规军队转变为远征军，在阿富汗和伊拉克作战。 Now, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-cant-afford-to-drop-the-ball-on-ukraine-u-k-foreign-secretary-says-95e6e5f8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">in the face of a bellicose Russia</a> , it is trying to be both but on a tight budget.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>英国表示，不会投资扩充军队，而是将重点放在采购技术上，“以确保我们的力量大于各部分之和”。该计划包括建立一支快速部署部队，可以赶往陷入困境的热点地区，以及一项确保更有效的武器采购系统的计划。政府还表示，在向乌克兰捐赠大量军火库后，将重新分配25亿英镑的国防预算，相当于约32亿美元，以补充弹药库存。</p><p>克里姆林宫入侵乌克兰并没有阻止英国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/news-explainers/how-british-storm-shadow-missiles-help-ukraines-counteroffensive/C0953C64-8212-4252-9D0B-CBE5C900CC49?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">——英国一直是基辅最大的政治和军事支持者之一</a>——计划将军队人数从82,000人削减至72,500人，使英国拥有自1714年以来最小的陆军部队该公司还正在积极采取行动，用 148 辆现代版挑战者坦克取代其 227 辆旧挑战者坦克。国防官员表示，乌克兰与俄罗斯的战斗表明，规模较小、装备精良的部队可以给规模更大的对手造成重大损失。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818397?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰新兵在英格兰南部的军事设施接受挑战者坦克操作训练。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Leon Neal/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>尽管如此，注重质量而非数量的决定凸显了资金短缺的欧洲国家在试图增强军事力量以阻止俄罗斯进一步侵略时面临的艰难选择。分析人士称，英国是北大西洋公约组织在欧洲的主要盟友之一，并且已经<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-and-allies-weigh-sending-ukraine-heavy-tanks-pointing-to-new-phase-of-the-war-11673292503?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在国防和援助乌克兰方面投入了大量资金</a>，但经过多年的预算削减，其军队已经被掏空。</p><p>乌克兰战斗造成的惨重伤亡——在一场激烈的冲突中消耗了大量的炮弹和装甲库存——也引发了分析人士和军事专家对英国专注于技术而不是规模的决定的质疑。英国议会国防委员会在本月的一份报告中得出结论：“英国目前的战斗装备储备极其有限，包括军舰、现代装甲车或战斗机。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Should Britain be expanding its military or upgrading its quality?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>自 20 世纪 80 年代中期以来，军费开支占英国国内生产总值的比例已减少一半，降至 2.2% 左右。英国首相苏纳克最近表示，未来两年将增加 50 亿英镑的军费开支。这笔资金将主要用于升级核防御系统和补充交给乌克兰的武器库存。</p><p>英国政府从 2020 年开始增加国防支出，今年英国历史上首次达到 500 亿英镑，但近期的增长大部分已被通货膨胀所抵消。苏纳克表示，英国的目标是将 GDP 的 2.5% 用于国防，但前提是经济情况允许。由于预计经济增长将持续多年缓慢，政府如果想加强军队，可能不得不削减其他公共服务。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EDA02BF5-0836-4277-AB7C-10442F70192F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdespite-ukraine-war-u-k-set-to-shrink-its-army-422e1424&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">拜登政府表示，计划向乌克兰发送集束弹药，以加强该国对俄罗斯军队的攻势。 《华尔街日报》解释了这些武器背后的技术以及它们为何引起人道主义担忧。插图：雅各布·亚历山大·尼尔森<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>与此同时，英国军方的高级领导层也即将进行改组。国防部长本·华莱士本周末表示，他将在今年晚些时候辞去这一职务。华莱士长期以来一直主张为军队提供更多资金，他警告说，如果没有额外的资金，英国军队将陷入困境。</p><p>英国陆军最高将领帕特里克·桑德斯 (Patrick Sanders) 在执掌两年后将于 2024 年卸任，任期比陆军许多人预期的要短。桑德斯最近在一次演讲中表示，英国不应该躲在北约盟友身后，依靠它们来弥补自己的军事缺口。华莱士否认英国在逃避责任，称英国需要一支装备精良而不仅仅是规模庞大的军队。</p><p>写信给马克斯·科尔切斯特<a href="mailto:Max.Colchester@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Max.Colchester@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 12:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/despite-ukraine-war-uk-set-to-shrink-its-army-422e1424</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/despite-ukraine-war-uk-set-to-shrink-its-army-422e1424<author><![CDATA[Max Colchester]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category></item></channel></rss>